  \times \mathbf{v}_f - (\mathbf{b}\cdot\mathbf{a})\mathbf{b} = \mathbf{v}_f \times \mathbf{b}$. Further, since $\mathbf{v}_f \times \mathbf{b}=-(\mathbf{b}\times\mathbf{v}_f)$, we can substitute this expression for $\mathbf{v}_f \times \mathbf{b}$ into the equation to get $(\mathbf{b} \cdot \mathbf{a}+1)\mathbf{b}=\mathbf{0}$. Clearly, we can not have $\mathbf{0}=1$, so $\mathbf{b=0}$, which is clearly impossible. If I in some way were to reach this conclusion in the question, this would be incorrect. One can instead arrive at the system of two vectors. Further, it also gives a value for $\mathbf{a}\cdot\mathbf{b} = 3$, which will not be useful. How can I solve this problem?</think>
<answer>Now, let's solve for $\mathbf{v}$. Since $\mathbf{v} \times \mathbf{b} = \mathbf{c} \times \mathbf{b}$, we have $\mathbf{v} = \mathbf{c} + k\mathbf{b}$ for some scalar $k$. We also have $\mathbf{v} \cdot \mathbf{a} = 0$, so $(\mathbf{c} + k\mathbf{b}) \cdot \mathbf{a} = 0$. Substituting the given vectors, we get $(\mathbf{a}, \mathbf{b}, \mathbf{c}, \mathbf{v}) = 10 + 7k = 0$, so $k = -\frac{10}{7}$. Therefore, the vector $\mathbf{v}$ is $\mathbf{v} = \mathbf{c} - \frac{10}{7}\mathbf{b} = \begin{pmatrix} \frac{22}{7} \\ -\frac{17}{7} \\ 10 \end{pmatrix}$. </answer>

